const e=[{q:"A single spark can start a prairie fire",s:'"A single spark can start a prairie fire" (January 1930)',e:"It is a metaphor that although new things have little power at the beginning, they have strong vitality and broad development prospects. When the revolution was at a low ebb and pessimism was spreading, Mao Zedong used this to encourage comrades to see hope and firmly believe that the power of the revolution will grow stronger."},{q:"Revolution is not treating guests to dinner, writing articles, or painting and embroidering. It cannot be so elegant, so leisurely, so gentle, so gentle, courteous, and thrifty. Revolution is a riot, a violent action in which one class overthrows another class",s:'"Inspection Report on the Peasant Movement in Hunan" (March 1927)',e:"Emphasizing that the essence of revolution is fierce class struggle, revolution cannot be replaced by moderate reform methods. In the face of heavy oppression, only by daring to fight can we truly change the fate of the oppressed."},{q:"Overcorrection must be excessive, but correction must not be excessive.",s:'"Inspection Report on the Peasant Movement in Hunan" (March 1927)',e:"To end the old feudal order, radical revolutionary methods rather than incremental reforms must be used. Breaking down entrenched old systems sometimes requires more than conventional efforts."},{q:"Without investigation, there is no right to speak.",s:'"Preface and Postscript to "Rural Survey"" (March 1941)',e:"All conclusions are drawn at the end of the investigation, not at the beginning. If you make random comments without doing research, you will fail ten times out of ten. This is the core of the ideological line of seeking truth from facts - proceeding from reality rather than subjective imagination."},{q:"Serve the people wholeheartedly",s:'"On Coalition Government" (April 1945)',e:"This is the fundamental purpose of our party and army. The starting point and end point of all work should be the interests of the people. These five words are the highest standard for testing all behaviors."},{q:"People are always going to die, but the meaning of death is different. To die for the benefit of the people is more important than Mount Tai",s:'"Serving the People" (September 1944)',e:"The value of life does not lie in its length, but in its purpose. If you devote your limited life to the cause of serving the people, such a death will be more important than Mount Tai. This is not only a tribute to Zhang Side, but also an inspiration to everyone."},{q:"Because we serve the people, if we have shortcomings, we are not afraid of others criticizing us and pointing them out.",s:'"Serving the People" (September 1944)',e:"A truly confident person is not afraid of criticism. Stick to whatever is in line with the interests of the people, and correct whatever is not in line with the interests of the people - this kind of mind and attitude is the guarantee for the continued progress of individuals and organizations."},{q:"We all come from all over the world and come together for a common revolutionary goal.",s:'"Serving the People" (September 1944)',e:"Regardless of origin or region, as long as the goal is the same, they can gather into a powerful force. This quote still inspires people of all backgrounds to work together."},{q:"Make up your mind, not be afraid of sacrifice, overcome all difficulties, and strive for victory",s:'"The Foolish Old Man Moves Mountains" (June 1945)',e:'This is the most powerful passage in "The Foolish Old Man Moves the Mountains". In the face of seemingly insurmountable odds, determination comes first. With determination and not being afraid of paying the price, no matter how big the difficulty is, you can overcome it step by step.'},{q:"We must persevere and work continuously, and we will also move God. This God is none other than the people of China",s:'"The Foolish Old Man Moves Mountains" (June 1945)',e:"The people are God, and persistent actions will eventually receive the response and support of the people. Don\u2019t be superstitious about external forces. The real power comes from the people."},{q:"When our comrades are in difficulties, we must see the achievements, see the light, and improve our courage.",s:'"Serving the People" (September 1944)',e:"In adversity, people's instinct is to see problems and difficulties, and Mao Zedong reminded us: we must take the initiative to look for the positive side. Seeing the results that have been achieved and the bright future ahead, courage naturally comes."},{q:"The Long March is a manifesto, the Long March is a propaganda team, and the Long March is a seeder",s:'"On Strategies to Oppose Japanese Imperialism" (December 1935)',e:'The Long March was more than just a military operation - it declared to the world the invincibility of the Red Army and sowed the seeds of revolution to the people along the way. Any great undertaking has a similar "long march" stage.'},{q:"Reading is learning, and using is also learning, and it is more important learning.",s:`"Strategic Issues in China's Revolutionary War" (December 1936)`,e:'Knowledge is valuable only when it is used. Many people stay at the "learning" stage, but real growth comes from "using" - testing, revising and deepening understanding in practice.'},{q:"Nothing is difficult in the world, as long as there are people who are willing",s:`"Strategic Issues in China's Revolutionary War" (December 1936)`,e:"The wisdom left by our ancestors was quoted by Mao Zedong in his military writings. As long as you are determined and willing to work hard, it is not difficult to get started and you can master it."},{q:"If you want to take it, you must first give it to it",s:`"Strategic Issues in China's Revolutionary War" (December 1936)`,e:"The wisdom of Laozi's Tao Te Ching was used in military strategy. Sometimes you have to give in in order to move forward, and you have to give in order to get something. This is a vivid embodiment of dialectics."},{q:"All reactionaries are paper tigers",s:'"A Conversation with American Journalist Anna Louise Strong" (August 1946)',e:"This famous quote shocked the world. Enemies who appear strong on the surface are weak in nature and in the long run because they are detached from the people. The truly powerful force is always on the side of the people."},{q:"The future is bright, but the road is tortuous",s:'"About the Chongqing Negotiations" (October 1945)',e:"Just ten words contain the simplest and most profound philosophy of life. We must have confidence in the future, and at the same time fully anticipate the difficulties ahead."},{q:"Ten thousand years is too long, seize the day",s:'"Manjianghong\xB7and Comrade Guo Moruo" (January 1963)',e:"Time waits for no one. Instead of sitting and waiting for the distant future, seize every moment in the present. This sentence has inspired generations of Chinese people to fight against time and struggle."},{q:"The long road through Xiongguan is really like iron, now we are crossing it from the beginning",s:`"Recalling Qin'e\xB7Loushanguan" (February 1935)`,e:`Loushanguan was a fierce battle in the Red Army's Long March. First write about the danger of the pass and the fierceness of the battle, and then write about the heroism after crossing it. No matter how difficult and dangerous the "passion" is, once you overcome it, you can start from a new starting point.`},{q:"The Red Army is not afraid of the difficulties of the expedition, and it can only wait for thousands of rivers and mountains",s:'"Seven Rules\xB7Long March" (October 1935)',e:"The Long March was beyond imagination, but in the eyes of the Red Army, it was nothing more than an easy task. This kind of effortless spirit comes from firm belief and lofty goals."},{q:"If you don\u2019t visit the Great Wall, you are not a true man",s:'"Qingpingle\xB7Liupanshan" (October 1935)',e:'The Long March over Liupan Mountain means that it is about to reach the northern Shaanxi base area. The "Great Wall" is both a geographical coordinate and a spiritual height - a true brave man will not give up until he achieves his goal.'},{q:"Count the famous people, but also look at the present day",s:'"Qinyuan Spring\xB7Snow" (February 1936)',e:"The ending of this poem is powerful. The heroes of history are all in the past, the real heroes are in the present and in the future. This is the expectation and inspiration for contemporary people."},{q:"Regardless of the wind and waves, it\u2019s better than taking a leisurely stroll",s:'"Water Melody Songtou\xB7Swimming" (June 1956)',e:"Sentences written while swimming in the Yangtze River. Not only am I not afraid of strong winds and waves, but I feel more comfortable than walking in the courtyard. This calmness comes from grasping the laws of nature and life."},{q:"For the sake of sacrifice and great ambition, I dare to teach the sun and the moon to change the sky",s:'"Qilu\xB7To Shaoshan" (June 1959)',e:"Because of the sacrifices of countless martyrs, the ambition to change the world was aroused. Today's achievements are hard-won, but we also need the courage to continue to change."},{q:"Complaining too much will prevent heartbreak. People should take a broad view of the scenery.",s:'"Qilu\xB7with Mr. Liu Yazi" (April 1949)',e:"Famous quotes to comfort friends. Complaining too much will only hurt yourself. It is better to broaden your horizons and take a long-term view. Dissatisfaction in life is often not worth mentioning in the larger time and space."},{q:"The spring breeze brings thousands of willows, and the 600 million Chinese states are all filled with Shun Yao",s:'"Two Songs of Seven Rhythms: Farewell to the God of Plague" (July 1958)',e:"When the people are organized and take initiative, everyone can become a sage like Yao and Shun. This is the highest praise for the creativity of the masses."},{q:"If there is love in the sky, the sky will also grow old, and the right path in the world will be vicissitudes of life.",s:`"Seven Rules: The People's Liberation Army Occupies Nanjing" (April 1949)`,e:"The laws of history are not subject to anyone's will. Although it is full of hardships to follow the trend of history and follow the right path, it is inevitable for the development of human society. The vicissitudes of life itself are the right path in the world."},{q:"You can go up to the nine heavens to catch the moon, and you can go down to the five oceans to catch turtles.",s:'"Shui Tiao Ge Tou Returns to Jinggangshan" (May 1965)',e:"Two very powerful sentences. Humans can land on the moon or dive into the deep ocean\u2014nothing is impossible. This is not only a prophecy of technological progress, but also a tribute to human subjective initiative."},{q:"Born to be a fairy cave, with infinite scenery on the dangerous peak",s:'"Qijue: Photos of the Immortal Cave in Mount Lu, taken by Comrade Li Jin" (September 1961)',e:"The most beautiful scenery is in the most dangerous places. If you don\u2019t go through hardships and obstacles, you won\u2019t be able to see the infinite scenery. This is the best motivation for those who strive."},{q:"Winning nationwide victory is only the first step in a long march of thousands of miles.",s:"Report of the Second Plenary Session of the Seventh Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (March 1949)",e:"A sober warning on the eve of the victory of the revolution: Don\u2019t be dazzled by victory, for greater challenges lie ahead. Any time you achieve something, it's just a new starting point."},{q:"We must ensure that comrades continue to maintain a modest, prudent, and non-arrogant and impetuous style of work.",s:"Report of the Second Plenary Session of the Seventh Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (March 1949)",e:'The "two musts" are self-awareness before going to Beijing to take the exam, and they are still important principles for life and work. The most dangerous enemies of success are pride and impatience.'},{q:"Practice, understand, practice again, understand again, this form repeats endlessly",s:'"On Practice" (July 1937)',e:"Understanding is not accomplished once, but is continuously deepened in repeated cycles of practice and understanding. Whatever you do, you must learn by doing, and then act while learning."},{q:"The fundamental cause of the development of things is not outside the thing but inside the thing",s:'"On Contradiction" (August 1937)',e:"When encountering a problem, you must first look for the cause within yourself rather than blaming the external environment. Internal factors are the basis for change, while external factors are just conditions."},{q:"External factors are the conditions for change, internal factors are the basis for change, and external factors work through internal factors.",s:'"On Contradiction" (August 1937)',e:"This is a classic proposition of dialectics. The environment is important, but the decisive factor is always you. Chickens can hatch from eggs at the right temperature, but they cannot hatch from stones."},{q:"If you are confident that you will live two hundred years, you will be like the water hitting three thousand miles.",s:'"Seven Ancient Fragments" (about 1917)',e:"Young Mao Zedong's self-motivating words. Filled with lofty sentiments, swallowing up mountains and rivers with great enthusiasm - having full confidence in one's own life, and wanting to gallop three thousand miles like a roc spreading its wings."},{q:"Thousands of enemy troops surrounded me, but I remained unmoved",s:'"Moon over Xijiang\xB7Jinggangshan" (Autumn 1928)',e:"A portrayal of Huang Yangjie during the war. Amidst the pressure from the outside world, keep your inner firmness and calmness. This determination comes from perseverance in belief."},{q:"People are still young when they travel through the green mountains, but the scenery here is unique",s:'"Qingpingle Huichang" (summer 1934)',e:"On the eve of the Long March, the situation was difficult, but the poet said: After walking through countless green mountains, he still did not age, and the scenery of this land in front of him was unique. Positive and optimistic revolutionary romanticism."},{q:"It is better to use the remaining courage to chase the poor bandits, not to be a famous academic overlord",s:`"Seven Rules: The People's Liberation Army Occupies Nanjing" (April 1949)`,e:"Use Xiang Yu's allusion to warn: Don't let Liu Bang go just because of fame and reputation like Xiang Yu did. Do things in one go without leaving any consequences."},{q:"The world is progressing and the future is bright. No one can change this general trend of history.",s:'"About the Chongqing Negotiations" (October 1945)',e:"This is the fundamental belief in the laws of history. No matter how many setbacks we face, the general direction of history is forward. If you maintain this belief, you will not be defeated by temporary difficulties."},{q:"Failure is the mother of success",s:`"Strategic Issues in China's Revolutionary War" (December 1936)`,e:"Every failure contains the seeds of success. The key is being able to learn from your failures. The fear of failure itself is the greatest failure."},{q:"The more difficult the place, the more you have to go to it. This is a good comrade.",s:'"About the Chongqing Negotiations" (October 1945)',e:"Face difficulties head on and don't run away. Difficult places are where you can make contributions, taking heavy responsibilities instead of light jobs."},{q:"A piece of white paper, no burden, easy to write the latest and most beautiful words, easy to draw the latest and most beautiful pictures",s:'"Introducing a Cooperative" (1958)',e:"Being backward and blank is not terrible, but means that there is no historical baggage and that we can start from scratch and create something new and beautiful."},{q:"Do it yourself, have enough food and clothing",s:'"Get Organized" (November 1943)',e:"Be self-reliant, don\u2019t wait and don\u2019t rely. In the midst of lockdowns and difficulties, only relying on your own hands can truly solve problems."},{q:"Power comes from the barrel of a gun",s:'"Problems of War and Strategy" (November 1938)',e:"In a class society, there is nothing without armed force. Peace is not achieved through prayer, but through strength and struggle."},{q:"Things in the world are complex and determined by various factors. Look at the problem from all aspects, not just from one side",s:'"About the Chongqing Negotiations" (October 1945)',e:"One-sidedness is a common thinking trap. Everything has many sides, and only by looking at it comprehensively and from multiple angles can we get closer to the truth."},{q:'Investigation and research are like "pregnancy in ten months", and solving problems is like "giving birth in one day"',s:'"Against Bookism" (May 1930)',e:"The investigation process before solving the problem takes time and patience like pregnancy; but once the investigation is sufficient, the solution is as natural as childbirth."},{q:"Chinese people are not afraid of death, so are they still afraid of difficulties?",s:'"Farewell, Stuart" (August 1949)',e:"Even the threat of death has come over, what kind of difficulties are there that cannot be overcome? This is a spirit of risking one's life to survive."},{q:"First understand clearly who is your friend and who is your opponent in society, and then decide how to act",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Analysis of the Classes in Chinese Society" (December 1925)',e:"This article emphasizes that route judgment cannot be based solely on passion, but must first identify the interests of each class. Find the right people to rely on and allies to prevent actions that go in the wrong direction."},{q:"The ability of a small base area to stand does not depend on luck, but on the coexistence of the masses, terrain, and enemy cracks.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Why Can China's Red Regime Exist?" \u300B(October 1928)`,e:"The article explains that the reason why some revolutionary forces can persevere is because they have a mass base and seize the enemy's internal contradictions and favorable geographical conditions. Any local breakthrough is inseparable from the judgment of the overall environment."},{q:"The team cannot just fight, but must also have political goals, organizational discipline and a unified style.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On Correcting Wrong Thoughts within the Party" (December 1929)',e:"This article focuses on correcting problems such as purely military views, extreme democratization, individualism and subjectivism, and emphasizes that the combat effectiveness of an organization comes from common goals and discipline."},{q:"Economic work is not an accessory of the revolution. The more difficult the situation, the more one must be able to settle accounts, organize, and produce.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Must Pay Attention to Economic Work" (August 1933)',e:"In the construction of base areas, finance, production and supply are not trivial matters. Whether you can live a stable life and organize resources well directly determines whether your career can be sustained."},{q:"When analyzing rural areas, we should not just look at slogans, but also look at how land, labor and actual benefits are distributed.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "How to Analyze Rural Classes" (October 1933)',e:"This type of analysis emphasizes identifying the positions of different groups based on real economic relationships. Determining who is oppressed, who has room for improvement, and who is wavering must depend on specific living conditions."},{q:"Policies must cover daily necessities, rice, oil and salt. Only when the people feel the benefits can the work be rooted.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Care for the Lives of the People and Pay Attention to Work Methods" (January 1934)',e:"The article reminds leaders that their work should not just focus on big goals. How well specific issues such as salt and rice, housing, medical care, and cattle farming are solved will directly determine whether the masses truly support it."},{q:"The united front is not something to be shouted out, it must be truly organized with the broadest possible force.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Struggle to Win Millions of People into the Anti-Japanese National United Front" (May 1937)',e:"The key is not the passionate expressions of a few people, but whether scattered groups of people can be turned into a force for common struggle. The more overall the task is, the more it relies on widespread mobilization."},{q:"Seeing a problem but pretending not to see it, being friendly on the surface often hurts the whole person in the end",s:'Theme is excerpted from "Against Liberalism" (September 1937)',e:"This article opposes treating unprincipled accommodation as solidarity. To be truly responsible is not to avoid conflicts, but to dare to point out problems and promote corrections for the common goal."},{q:"Victory rarely comes from quick thinking. Look at the long-term conditions first and then arrange the stages and rhythm.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On Protracted War" (May 1938)',e:"The core of the article is not just to have confidence in the prospects, but to judge the enemy and our forces, the international environment, political mobilization and strategic stages together to avoid blind pessimism or blind optimism."},{q:"Even if you are on a united front, you must maintain your own judgment, organization and initiative.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Problem of Independence and Autonomy in the United Front" (November 1938)',e:"Cooperation does not mean giving up a position. Only by maintaining independent thinking and organizational skills, cooperation will not become a passive follower."},{q:"If there is no clear propaganda, organization and cadres to carry out the political line, it will soon lose its shape.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Communists" (October 1939)',e:"This article emphasizes the linkage between party building, the united front and armed struggle. The correct route requires the support of ideas, organization and communication tools."},{q:"Real learning is not about memorizing a set of ready-made explanations, but using theory to explain the problems in China at hand.",s:"Theme is excerpted from Transforming Our Learning (May 1941)",e:"The article focuses on criticizing subjectivism and dogmatism, emphasizing that learning should be combined with investigation and research, historical experience and practical problems, and ultimately settle on solving specific problems."},{q:"Work style rectification is not just a gesture, but a real suppression of subjectivism, sectarianism and empty words",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Rectifying the Party's Style" (February 1942)`,e:"The article calls for cleaning up bad styles in terms of thinking, methods and organizational life. Style issues may seem abstract, but they will eventually turn into inefficiencies, gaps and misjudgments at work."},{q:"If articles and speeches are empty and cliche, the correct meaning will not be conveyed to people's hearts.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Eight-legged Opposition Party Writing" (February 1942)',e:"This article opposes expressions that are divorced from reality, divorced from objects, and have rigid language. Persuading people does not rely on a bunch of concepts, but on facts, logic and words that can be understood."},{q:"Literature and art cannot float in mid-air. It must always respond to people\u2019s real lives, emotions and situations.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Speech at the Yan'an Forum on Literature and Art" (May 1942)`,e:"This speech discusses the service objects and creative stance of literature and art. The core is not to compress creation, but to emphasize that the work should be connected with real society."},{q:"When doing work, we should not only have a general call for it, but also focus on a few points to do it thoroughly.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Some Questions Concerning the Methods of Leadership" (June 1943)',e:"The article proposes the combination of general and individual, and the combination of leadership and the masses. It is not enough to have a big slogan, you must first gain local experience and then promote it to a wider range."},{q:"The truly valuable spirit is to take other people\u2019s careers as one\u2019s own responsibility",s:'The theme is excerpted from "In Memory of Bethune" (December 1939)',e:"This article uses Bethune's deeds to emphasize selflessness, responsibility and excellence. It serves as a reminder that professionalism and public spirit are not separate."},{q:"It is not enough to be able to fight, you must also be able to organize production, manage supplies and improve life",s:'The theme is excerpted from "We Must Learn to Do Economic Work" (January 1945)',e:"The article emphasizes that economic work is not a matter for a few departments, but is fundamental work related to the overall situation. Without stable production and supply, many goals are unsustainable."},{q:"The most common mistake after victory is to think of new difficulties too simply",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Current Situation and Our Policies after the Victory of the Anti-Japanese War" (August 1945)',e:"At a turning point in the situation, the article reminds people to stay awake. As the overall situation moves forward, it is even more important to distinguish between surface opportunities and long-term risks."},{q:"The power is no longer evenly distributed, but the advantages are concentrated at the critical moment where the results can be determined.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Concentrate superior forces and annihilate the enemy individually" (September 1946)',e:"This article emphasizes that it is not to strive for strength everywhere, but to concentrate on the most certain point. When resources are limited, choice is more important than recklessness."},{q:"Those who lead a team must first get the group of people to move, rather than doing everything themselves.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Working Methods of Party Committees" (March 1949)',e:"The article compared the secretary to a squad leader and emphasized division of labor, collaboration, ventilation and collective decision-making. Leadership is not just personal ability, but also the ability to organize others to get things done."},{q:"For the new regime to stand firm, it must not only have the people's stance, but also have institutional arrangements that can protect the interests of the majority.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "On the People's Democratic Dictatorship" (June 1949)`,e:"The article discusses the nature of the country, the position of the people and the basis of political power. The core is to use the system to stabilize the interests, organization and action capabilities of the majority of people."},{q:"The better the conditions get, the more we need to remember the restraint, simplicity and tenacity we had when starting a business.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Always Maintain the Style of Hard Struggle" (October 1949)',e:"The reminder of this article is very direct: after the environment improves, people are most likely to relax, show off, and forget their true colors. Hard work is first of all a kind of mental restraint."},{q:"When the situation is just stable, it is not advisable to make enemies everywhere. You must first stabilize the order and distinguish priorities.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Don't Attack on All Sides" (June 1950)`,e:"The article emphasizes the strategic rhythm in the new situation. We cannot push all contradictions to the extreme at the same time, but we must first grasp the main issues and strive for more forces that can be united."},{q:"If we want to improve the financial and economic situation, we cannot rely solely on passion, but we must also focus on order, restoration and gradual reversal.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Struggle for a Basic Improvement in the National Financial and Economic Situation" (June 1950)',e:"This article emphasizes that the restoration of the national economy must be arranged in stages, and opposes both inaction and hasty and hasty progress that is divorced from the basics."},{q:"To build a country is not to focus on one end alone, but to coordinate the priorities, coastal and inland areas, central and local governments, and individuals of the country.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On Ten Major Relationships" (April 1956)',e:"The value of the article lies in dealing with complex relationships. Truly mature governance is not simply taking sides, but seeking a balance between multiple tensions and activating the enthusiasm of all parties."},{q:"There are conflicts of different natures in society, and the way to deal with them cannot be measured with a ruler.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Correct Handling of Contradictions Among the People" (February 1957)',e:"This article emphasizes distinguishing the nature of contradictions and opposes simplistic treatment. Many problems, if handled improperly, will push things that could be coordinated into opposition."},{q:"When doing construction, we must mobilize the enthusiasm of most people, and we must not shrink the circle smaller and smaller.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Correct Handling of Contradictions Among the People" (February 1957)',e:"The article proposes overall consideration and appropriate arrangements. To do big things, we cannot only serve a few links, but must consider the acceptance and participation of a wider group of people."},{q:"Saving is not a quick fix, but a long-term effective way of working when resources are limited.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Correct Handling of Contradictions Among the People" (February 1957)',e:"The article puts conservation into the long-term conditions of national construction. The more large-scale construction is, the more we must oppose extravagance, bureaucracy and high consumption."},{q:"Learning from others does not mean copying. The real skill is to turn other people\u2019s strengths into your own.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On Ten Major Relationships" (April 1956)',e:"The article emphasizes the need to learn from foreign experience but not to lose independent judgment. Copying is the easiest, but often the most unsuitable for your own conditions."},{q:"The closer the relationship between cadres and the masses is, the easier it will be to find solutions to many seemingly intractable problems.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Persevere in Hard Struggle and Closely Contact the Masses" (March 1957)',e:"This kind of speech continues the same work clue: style is not a slogan, but whether you can go deep into the scene, hear the real voice, and reduce the barriers."},{q:"When things change, the biggest fear is to look at today\u2019s situation through yesterday\u2019s eyes",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Things Are Changing" (May 1957)',e:"When the situation changes, old judgments may become obsolete immediately. The article reminds people to revise their understanding in a timely manner, neither to be slow nor to use emotions instead of analysis."},{q:"The value of propaganda work is not to be louder, but to be able to explain the truth to a place where people can accept it.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Speech at the National Propaganda Work Conference of the Communist Party of China" (March 1957)',e:"This type of discussion emphasizes that publicity and education must have a sense of object and method. Only pursuing posture and not caring about the effect will only increase the estrangement in the end."},{q:"For different opinions, first distinguish the right from wrong and their nature, and then decide whether it is an argument, help or restriction.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On Ten Major Relationships" (April 1956)',e:"When dealing with the relationship between the party and non-party, right and non, the article emphasizes that principles should be adhered to while leaving room for expression and correction of different opinions."},{q:"Bad things may not just get worse. The key lies in whether you can find lessons from them and turn around in time.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Correct Handling of Contradictions Among the People" (February 1957)',e:"This article emphasizes the transformative nature of contradictions and events. As long as it is handled properly, frustration, conflict and even chaos may force improvements."},{q:"Standing in one place is not to be conservative, but to accumulate strength and act steadily.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Struggle in Jinggangshan" (November 1928)',e:"This article focuses on the relationship between the base area, the armed forces and the masses, emphasizing the need to build during the struggle, rather than just pursuing short-term mobile operations."},{q:"If policies cannot restore production and smooth exchanges, many goals will be defeated.",s:"Theme is excerpted from Our Economic Policy (January 1934)",e:"The article emphasizes that economic policies must not only take care of basic people's livelihood, but also serve the overall situation. They cannot just talk about slogans and ignore resources and order."},{q:"To judge grand strategy, we must not only look at the immediate pressure, but also whether the resistance can unite into national strength.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Principles, Methods and Prospects for Opposing Japan's Offensive" (July 1937)`,e:"This article focuses on the judgment of the situation on the eve of the all-out war of resistance, emphasizing that we must first unify understanding and then act in unison in the face of complex threats."},{q:"When a big task comes, the most important thing is to mobilize the scattered people and resources.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Struggle to Mobilize All Forces for Victory in the Anti-Japanese War" (August 1937)',e:"The article emphasizes that the war of resistance is not a matter for a few people, but must become an organized action of the whole society."},{q:"After cooperation begins, the real test has just begun",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Urgent Tasks after the Establishment of Cooperation between the Kuomintang and the Communist Party" (September 1937)',e:"The article reminds people that the establishment of a united front does not mean that the problem will be solved automatically. What is more critical is that cooperation should be brought to the actual task and execution level."},{q:"To explain yourself to the outside world is not only to strive for understanding, but also to strive for the initiative.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "A Conversation with the British Journalist Bertrand" (October 1937)',e:"This type of conversation text reflects the ability to express domestic struggles in the context of international public opinion and world patterns."},{q:"The tighter the situation becomes, the less we can just focus on the losses, but also look at how to organize a counterattack in the future.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Situation and Tasks of the Anti-Japanese War after the Fall of Shanghai and Taiyuan" (November 1937)',e:"The article reiterates its persistence in resisting the war and continuing mobilization after a major defeat, and opposes overall pessimism due to temporary losses."},{q:"The weak side must turn space, mass and mobility into its own weapons",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Strategic Issues in the Anti-Japanese Guerrilla War" (May 1938)',e:"The article systematically discusses how guerrilla warfare serves the overall strategy, demonstrating that flexible warfare is not a piecemeal attempt at luck."},{q:"If you want to take on a leadership role, you must first take actual responsibility in the most difficult places.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Position of the Chinese Communist Party in the National War" (October 1938)',e:"This article emphasizes that the party's status comes from responsibility and performance in actual struggles, rather than self-declaration."},{q:"A youth movement that can truly leave an impact must be connected with the general direction of society.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The May Fourth Movement" (May 1939)',e:"The article uses the commemoration of the May Fourth Movement to illustrate that young people are not an isolated group, and their direction must be judged in the context of national and social changes."},{q:"The most valuable thing about youth is not enthusiasm itself, but putting enthusiasm in the right direction",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Direction of the Youth Movement" (May 1939)',e:"This article emphasizes the relationship between youth growth and the tasks of the times, and opposes only gestures without direction."},{q:"The situation is changing, and the tasks must also change. We cannot cling to old experiences.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Current Situation and the Tasks of the Party" (October 1939)',e:"The article emphasizes the need to adjust work priorities according to the new situation and connect judgment and execution."},{q:"The bigger your business is, the less you can rely solely on people with one background and one type of experience.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Absorbing a Large Number of Intellectuals" (December 1939)',e:"The article emphasizes the importance of broadly absorbing intellectuals. The key is to involve more professional forces in the common goal."},{q:"To understand a revolution, we must first understand the country\u2019s historical conditions and realistic structure.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Chinese Revolution and the Chinese Communist Party" (December 1939)',e:"The article systematically sorts out the nature of Chinese society, revolutionary objects and stage tasks, and emphasizes understanding the path based on national conditions."},{q:"The transitional stage cannot be smoothed out in one sentence. The system design must be consistent with the actual conditions.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On New Democracy" (January 1940)',e:"This article discusses the revolutionary stage and the direction of political culture, emphasizing that the new stage requires matching systems and ideological expression."},{q:"When it comes to political form, the key is not the name, but whether it can carry the interests of the majority of people.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Constitutional Government of New Democracy" (February 1940)',e:"When the article discusses constitutionalism, it does not stop at formal imitation, but emphasizes that the political system must serve real social changes."},{q:"The base area must be stable, not only with the army, but also with political arrangements that can be recognized by the masses.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Problems of Political Power in the Anti-Japanese Base Areas" (March 1940)',e:"The article focuses on political power construction, representation and governance methods, explaining that organizational form is as critical as the foundation of popular support."},{q:"The strategy of the united front is not to please everyone, but to keep the principles and rhythm steady.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Strategic Issues in the Current Anti-Japanese United Front" (March 1940)',e:"The article emphasizes that in an environment where cooperation and struggle coexist, one can neither advance rashly nor lose one's position."},{q:"In the face of oppression, the most effective response is often not to retreat, but to build one's own strength more solidly.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Let go of developing anti-Japanese forces and resist the attacks of anti-communist die-hards" (May 1940)',e:"The article emphasizes that in a stressful environment, it is still necessary to expand the mass base and organizational capabilities to proactively resolve the passive situation."},{q:"True unity is not about temporary harmony, but about persisting under long-term pressure.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "United to the End" (July 1940)',e:"The article emphasizes that adhering to unity requires not only principles, but also patience and continuity."},{q:"Policies are not abstract preferences, but concrete methods to deal with real-life conflicts.",s:'Theme is excerpted from "On Policy" (December 1940)',e:"This article reminds people that it is not enough to have a correct route, but also to turn it into a policy that adapts to different regions and objects."},{q:"Every time you withstand a shock, you must summarize your experience into methods that can be used in the future.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Summary on Defeating the Second Anti-Communist Upsurge" (May 1941)',e:"The article emphasizes that in response to political and military pressure, we should not only focus on short-term gains and losses, but also develop replicable response experience."},{q:"When looking at the international situation, we should not just listen to superficial rhetoric, but look at who is exchanging greater crises in the name of peace.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Uncovering the Munich Conspiracy in the Far East" (May 1941)',e:"This article emphasizes identifying compromises and transfers in international politics, and opposes mistaking concessions for stability."},{q:"When a large common enemy appears, we must learn to find forces that can be united in a wider range",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the International United Front Against Fascism" (June 1941)',e:"The article puts the domestic struggle into the international anti-fascist pattern and emphasizes that common interests can form a greater alliance."},{q:"Governance ability is not an abstract title. It depends on whether the place can be truly organized.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Speech at the Council of the Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia Border Region" (November 1941)',e:"This type of speech reflects the emphasis on representation, order and practical effects in the construction of border region political power."},{q:"If key policies are grasped correctly, they can bring about changes in the entire situation.",s:'Theme is excerpted from "A Policy of Extreme Importance" (September 1942)',e:"The article emphasizes identifying decisive links in complex work and leveraging a few key policies to leverage overall improvement."},{q:"The real turning point often occurs when the balance of power and people's expectations are rewritten at the same time.",s:'Theme is excerpted from "The Turning Point of World War II" (October 1942)',e:"The article uses the changes in the world war situation to remind people that when judging a turning point, we should not just look at one or two battles, but look at the overall trend."},{q:"Once the finances are in chaos, many political and military objectives will be affected.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Economic and Financial Problems during the Anti-Japanese War" (December 1942)',e:"The article systematically discusses wartime finance and economic work, emphasizing that production, distribution and burdens must form a sustainable relationship."},{q:"Some issues cannot be dealt with vaguely. When it is time to ask questions, the responsibilities must be clearly stated.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Questioning the Kuomintang" (July 1943)',e:"The article embodies the strategy of publicly revealing contradictions and forcing the other side to take a stand in political struggles."},{q:"To truly stabilize the base areas, we must focus on the economy, military-civilian relations, and the interests of the masses.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Carrying out the Movement of Rent Reduction, Production and Supporting the Government and Loving the People in the Base Area" (October 1943)',e:"The article emphasizes that several seemingly scattered tasks actually support each other and cannot be promoted in isolation."},{q:"If you cannot respond to the situation at hand, no matter how hard you study, it will be easy to fail.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Learning and Current Affairs" (April 1944)',e:"The article links learning with the current situation and emphasizes that theoretical improvement must serve realistic judgment and practical work."},{q:"When listening to political statements, you should not just listen to whether the words sound good or not, but also what they avoid.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Commentary on Chiang Kai-shek's Speech on Double Tenth Day" (October 1944)`,e:"By analyzing the opponent's speech, the article reminds people to look at the essence of the problem from the gaps, avoidances and contradictions."},{q:"There are also unions and divisions in the cultural field. It is not only the battlefield and the political arena that have a united front.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The United Front in Cultural Work" (October 1944)',e:"The article explains that cultural work is not a marginal matter, but is closely related to political direction and social mobilization."},{q:"The worse the conditions are, the more we need to learn to organize production in the gaps.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Production can also be carried out in guerrilla zones" (January 1945)',e:"The article emphasizes that difficult areas are not just for consumption. As long as the method is right, production capacity can still be maintained and restored."},{q:"In the face of major bifurcations, what matters is not the details of winning or losing, but which path represents the future.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Destiny of Two Chinas" (April 1945)',e:"The article compares the two prospects together and emphasizes that the choice of path determines the fate of the country."},{q:"The larger the organization, the more it must work on both style and supply.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Self-Sufficiency of Military Production and the Importance of the Two Major Movements of Rectification and Production" (April 1945)',e:"The article points out that rectifying work style and improving production are not two separate things. They jointly determine the sustainability of the team."},{q:"After seeing through the performance, it is more important to judge why the performance cannot be performed.",s:`Theme is excerpted from "Hurley and Chiang Kai-shek's Double Act Has Been Broken" (July 1945)`,e:"By revealing the bankruptcy of political performance, the article emphasizes that the balance of power and the basis of public opinion are the decisive factors."},{q:"The last moment is often the most test of concentration. Don\u2019t relax just because you are close to victory.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Last Battle Against the Japanese Invaders" (August 1945)',e:"The article emphasizes that when victory is approaching, we must still maintain organization and action, and make the final step steady."},{q:"When others make a situation worse, you must first clarify your responsibility and the truth.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Chiang Kai-shek is Provoking Civil War" (August 1945)',e:"The article strives for political initiative and social judgment by revealing the attribution of responsibility for provoking the civil war."},{q:"To identify an attack, look not only at what is said verbally, but also at the strength, deployment, and actions of the troops",s:`The theme is excerpted from "The Truth About the Kuomintang's Offensive" (November 1945)`,e:"The article emphasizes that the judgment of the situation must be based on facts and cannot be biased by packaging words."},{q:"Defending a region depends not only on fighting, but also on making people's lives comfortable.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Rent reduction and production are the two major events in defending the liberated areas" (November 1945)',e:"The article raised rent reduction and production to a strategic level, explaining that the economy and people's livelihood are part of the line of defense."},{q:"Before the new year begins, set the direction, order and priorities first, so that it will not be easy to mess up later.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Principles for Work in the Liberated Areas in 1946" (December 1945)',e:"The article emphasizes the importance of phased policies and uses clear task arrangements to improve overall coordination."},{q:"After entering a key area, seek firm ground first and then discuss expansion.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Establishing a Solid Northeast Base Area" (December 1945)',e:"The article reminds us that when working in new areas, we should not just focus on speed, but also take into account mass work, military deployment and governance foundation."},{q:"When you are in a passive situation, you must also find a way to take the initiative back.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Smashing Chiang Kai-shek's Offensive with a War of Self-Defense" (July 1946)`,e:"The article emphasizes that in a defensive war, the situation can still be reversed through correct organization and battlefield selection."},{q:"Some mediations are not to solve problems, but to shape a situation that is beneficial to oneself.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "The Truth about American "Mediation" and the Prospects of China's Civil War" (September 1946)`,e:"The article reminds people to identify the logic of interests behind external intervention and not to regard formal neutrality as true neutrality."},{q:"When the situation is stalemate, stage summary is more reliable than emotional judgment",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Three Months Summary" (October 1946)',e:"The article embodies the idea of using stage reviews to stabilize team judgment and correction methods in continuous struggles."},{q:"The climax is not something to shout out, but to take the initiative to meet it after it has accumulated to a certain level.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Welcoming the New Upsurge of the Chinese Revolution" (February 1947)',e:"The article emphasizes that when the situation becomes stronger, we must not only see opportunities, but also be prepared to take on greater responsibilities."},{q:"A real siege is not just military, it is political and social",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Chiang Kai-shek's Government is Surrounded by the Whole People" (May 1947)`,e:"The article explains why opponents are becoming increasingly isolated from the perspective of mass base and social relations."},{q:"As the war enters a new stage, methods must also be upgraded",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Strategic Guidelines for the Second Year of the Liberation War" (September 1947)',e:"The article focuses on strategic arrangements for the second year, emphasizing that stage transition requires new deployments rather than repetition."},{q:"If an army wants to go far, it must clearly explain why it is fighting.",s:`The theme is excerpted from the "Declaration of the Chinese People's Liberation Army" (October 1947)`,e:"The importance of the text of the declaration lies in unifying goals, boundaries and disciplines and giving actions a clear political direction."},{q:"Seeing the task clearly means not only knowing what to do, but also knowing what to do first",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Present Situation and Our Tasks" (December 1947)',e:"The article emphasizes that when the overall situation is favorable, it is even more important to distinguish priorities and not let local complexity hold back the general direction."},{q:"The larger the organization, the more inseparable it is from the return of timely, true, and comparable information.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On Establishing a Reporting System" (January 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes that the value of a reporting system is to base decisions on actual conditions rather than imagination."},{q:"If the deviations in the policy are not clarified in time, the implementation level will become more and more fragmented.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Several Important Issues in Current Party Policies" (January 1948)',e:"The article clarifies several key issues, reflecting the importance of unified understanding for unified action."},{q:"The enthusiasm within the team is not only based on orders, but also depends on the sense of participation and trust.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Democratic Movement within the Army" (January 1948)',e:"The article discusses the role of democracy within the military, emphasizing that it serves unity, education, and combat effectiveness."},{q:"When the same policy enters different regions, the approach cannot be completely one-size-fits-all",s:'Theme is excerpted from "Different Strategies for Enforcing Land Law in Different Areas" (February 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes that policy implementation must respect regional differences and retain strategic flexibility while maintaining consistent principles."},{q:"Once propaganda goes too far, it often distorts issues that are originally controllable.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Correcting "Left" Errors in Land Reform Propaganda" (February 1948)',e:"The article reminds us to avoid simplification and exaggeration in mass work and maintain a sense of scale."},{q:"When entering a new area to carry out reforms, first clearly explain the boundaries, steps and key points.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Key Points of Land Reform in the New Liberated Areas" (February 1948)',e:"The article focuses on sorting out the basic principles of land reform in the newly liberated areas to prevent distortion of implementation."},{q:"When dealing with industrial and commercial issues, we should not just look at our stance, but also whether it is beneficial to the overall situation.",s:'Theme is excerpted from "On Industrial and Commercial Policy" (February 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes the need to find a balance between developing production, stabilizing order and policy direction."},{q:"In complex situations, you must learn to distinguish between levels and not lump all objects into one category.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Question of the National Bourgeoisie and the Enlightened Gentlemen" (March 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes the ability of discrimination in united front work and opposes simplistic viewing of various social forces."},{q:"What cadres fear most is not being busy, but being busy for a long time without following the mass line",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Speech at the Shanxi-Suiyuan Cadres Conference" (April 1948)',e:"The speech focused on land, policies and cadre style, emphasizing that all work must ultimately return to the basis of the masses."},{q:"Running a newspaper is not about talking to oneself, but about making the really important things clear to the masses.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Conversations with Editorial Staff of Jinsui Daily" (April 1948)',e:"The article discusses how journalism serves real struggles, emphasizing language, stance and sense of object."},{q:"The most important thing when working in new areas is to be stable, accurate and step-by-step, rather than seeking speed all at once.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Strategic Issues in Rural Work in Newly Liberated Areas" (May 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes the rhythm and strategies of rural work to prevent copying of experience and hasty advancement."},{q:"The faster the reform advances, the more necessary it is to rectify the team itself simultaneously",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Land Reform Work and Party Consolidation Work in 1948" (May 1948)',e:"The article mentions land reform and party consolidation together, indicating that the success or failure of policies is inseparable from organizational purity and execution capabilities."},{q:"The value of a sound system lies in not relying on individuals to fill holes on the spot at critical times.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On Improving the Party Committee System" (September 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes that the party committee system is not a formality, but a mechanism for collective leadership to truly operate stably."},{q:"In the face of common oppression, cross-regional unity is a strength in itself",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Revolutionary Forces of the World Unite to Oppose Imperialist Aggression" (November 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes the commonality of anti-imperialist struggles from an international perspective and opposes viewing national movements in isolation."},{q:"When major changes come, it is more important to accurately judge the trend first than to dwell on local details.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "Major Changes in China's Military Situation" (November 1948)`,e:"The article emphasizes that the military situation should be viewed from the perspective of changes in overall strength, rather than being led by scattered results."},{q:"The most difficult thing about many careers is not the beginning, but whether you can continue to the end when you reach the critical point.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Carrying the Revolution to the End" (December 1948)',e:"The article emphasizes maintaining determination and continuity when victory is approaching and preventing midway pauses."},{q:"When an era truly turns a page, the sign is that most people begin to regard the country as their own business.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Chinese People Stand Up" (September 1949)',e:"This speech centered on the historical significance of the founding of New China, emphasizing the dominant position and the transition of the times."},{q:"Great unity is not an abstract tribute, but the most basic political resource of a new country.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Long Live the Great Unity of the Chinese People" (September 1949)',e:"The article emphasizes the importance of different forces coming together for a common cause and elevates unity as the foundation of nation-building."},{q:"A firm stance is not only clear verbally, but also reflected in whether you dare to stick to the end at key points.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Being a Complete Revolutionary" (June 1950)',e:"The article emphasizes that the integrity of the revolutionaries is reflected in their consistent actions, firm style and responsibility."},{q:"A true role model is not one who is praised, but one who can lead others to raise their standards together.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "You Are a Model Figure for the Whole Nation" (September 1950)',e:"This speech emphasizes the demonstration and backbone role of advanced figures, making role models a part of organizational mobilization."},{q:"The stronger you are, the more you must know how to exercise restraint, and the less discipline you must lose on the battlefield.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "The Chinese People's Volunteers Must Protect the Mountains, Waters, Plants and Trees of North Korea" (January 1951)`,e:"The article links internationalism, military discipline and mass relations, emphasizing that style is also combat effectiveness."},{q:"When dealing with acute issues, we must rely more on the masses and pay attention to facts and procedures",s:`The theme is excerpted from "The Party's Mass Line Must Be Implemented to Suppress Counterrevolution" (May 1951)`,e:"The article emphasizes that even in high-pressure struggles, we cannot deviate from the mass line and investigation and verification."},{q:"Whether a large-scale campaign can be effective depends on whether it reaches the places with the deepest abuses.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Great Victory of the Three Movements" (October 1951)',e:"The article summarizes the results of several campaigns and emphasizes the joint significance of anti-corruption, anti-waste and anti-bureaucracy."},{q:"Cleaning up old abuses does not just rely on investigating a few cases, but taking the opportunity to rebuild morals and order.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Struggle between the "Three Antis" and the "Five Antis" (November 1951)',e:"The article links the special struggle with political power construction, economic order and cadre style."},{q:"After the situation changes, the main contradiction will also change accordingly, and we cannot always stick to the old judgment.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Contradiction between the Working Class and the Bourgeoisie is the Main Domestic Contradiction" (June 1952)',e:"The article emphasizes that as social structure changes, the key contradictions in domestic work need to be re-identified."},{q:"Unity is not a confused mess. When boundaries are clear, cooperation becomes more stable.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Unite and draw a clear line between ourselves and the enemy" (August 1952)',e:"The article emphasizes that while striving for unity, we must maintain principled boundaries and avoid confusing objects."},{q:"Once an organization loses touch with reality, the first thing that often grows is bureaucracy.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Opposing Bureaucracy, Commandism and Law and Discipline" (January 1953)',e:"The article focuses on criticizing several harmful styles and reminds us that formalism and chaos must be prevented in the construction of political power."},{q:"When leading young people, we should not just ask them to be like old comrades, but we must also understand their rhythms and characteristics.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Work of the Youth League Should Take Care of the Characteristics of Youth" (June 1953)',e:"The article emphasizes that when doing youth work, we must respect the differences between the target groups and organize and guide them in appropriate ways."},{q:"When dealing with transitional forms, the key is not whether the name is pure or not, but whether it is conducive to the overall transformation.",s:'Theme is excerpted from "On State Capitalism" (July 1953)',e:"The article discusses the role of state capitalism in the transition period and emphasizes judging the value of policies from actual results."},{q:"After the stage transition, there must be a general line that can unify the scattered tasks.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "The Party's General Line during the Transition Period" (August 1953)`,e:"The article emphasizes the use of a general line to unify the tasks of industrialization, transformation and construction to avoid each doing his own thing."},{q:"The significance of a victory is not only to end the war, but also to change how it will proceed in the future.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Great Victory and Future Tasks in the War to Resist U.S. Aggression and Aid Korea" (September 1953)',e:"The article summarizes the political and strategic significance of resisting U.S. aggression and aiding Korea, and at the same time turns its attention to post-war construction and preparations."},{q:"The value of institutional texts lies in stabilizing and clarifying the direction that has been formed.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "About the Draft Constitution of the People's Republic of China" (June 1954)`,e:"The article clarifies the design of the national system around the draft constitution and implements the principled goals into institutional expression."},{q:"What is most needed during the construction period is not just enthusiasm, but the transformation of long-term goals into sustained actions.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Struggle to Build a Great Socialist Country" (September 1954)',e:"This speech emphasized the long-term nature of nation-building and required the integration of political goals, economic work, and organizational capabilities."},{q:"No matter how great the threat is, if it cannot scare away people\u2019s will, it will not be able to scare the future.",s:`The theme is excerpted from "The Atomic Bomb Can't Frighten the Chinese People" (January 1955)`,e:"The article emphasizes the need to maintain strategic calm in the face of nuclear threats and opposes giving up independent positions in fear."},{q:"Holding a conference is not to repeat conclusions, but to take the opportunity to explain the problems and directions to another level.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Speech at the National Congress of the Communist Party of China" (March 1955)',e:"The speech emphasized the need to unify understanding, rectify work styles and advance key tasks in the new construction environment."},{q:"The key to organizing scattered small-scale production is not to rush it more urgently, but to let it see the way out.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "On the Problem of Agricultural Cooperativeization" (July 1955)',e:"The article discusses the differences in the promotion of agricultural cooperativeization and emphasizes the relationship between direction judgment and mass acceptance."},{q:"Any reform must find the most reliable mobilizing backbone and cannot be promoted solely by documents.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Agricultural Cooperation Must Rely on Party and League Members and Poor and Lower-Middle Peasants" (September 1955)',e:"The article emphasizes the issue of relying on the strength of cooperation and explains that organizational advancement requires a clear main body foundation."},{q:"What\u2019s really worth watching about a debate is what deeper differences of position are reflected behind it",s:'The theme is excerpted from "A Debate on Agricultural Cooperativeization and the Current Class Struggle" (October 1955)',e:"The article places the debate on cooperativity in the context of larger social conflicts and emphasizes that differences of opinion are not just disputes over technical lines."},{q:"To transform traditional industries, we must not only have a direction, but also let practitioners see the way to survive after transformation.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Accelerating the Socialist Transformation of Handicraft Industry" (March 1956)',e:"The article discusses the necessity and promotion methods of handicraft industry transformation, emphasizing that reform must be connected with real livelihoods."},{q:"After an organization has gone far, it is even more important to look back and see which traditions cannot be lost.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Strengthening Party Unity and Inheriting Party Tradition" (August 1956)',e:"The article emphasizes that unity is not about eliminating differences, but about maintaining overall unity based on common traditions and principles."},{q:"One of the most important skills of local leaders is to connect the central spirit with local reality",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Speech at the Meeting of Provincial, Municipal and Autonomous Region Party Committee Secretaries" (January 1957)',e:"The speech discussed the methods and relationship handling in work in various places, emphasizing the initiative of both the central and local governments."},{q:"The core of leadership is not to ban people in name only, but to organize everyone on key issues.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Communist Party of China is the Core of Leadership of the All Chinese People" (May 1957)',e:"The article emphasizes that leadership comes from historical role and actual ability. In the final analysis, it depends on whether one can assume overall responsibility."},{q:"In the face of concentrated attacks, first establish your own organizational skills and judgment.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Organizing Strength to Counterattack the Rampant Attacks of Rightists" (June 1957)',e:"The article emphasizes that in ideological and political struggles, responses must not be loose but must be organized in a planned manner."},{q:"Fight back not with greater emotion, but with clearer boundaries and more stable organizations",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Repelling the Offensive of the Bourgeois Right" (July 1957)',e:"The article focuses on how to respond to the right-wing offensive, emphasizing that initiative comes from clear judgment and organization and execution."},{q:"Those who promote progress not only oppose backwardness, but also push things forward",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Being a Promoter of the Revolution" (October 1957)',e:"The article emphasizes that revolutionaries must not only criticize problems, but also bear the responsibility of construction and promotion."},{q:"When there is a lot of noise, what is really important is not to lose sight of most people",s:'The theme is excerpted from "Firmly Believe in the Majority of the Masses" (October 1957)',e:"The article emphasizes that believing in the majority of the masses is the fundamental premise for political judgment and working methods."},{q:"Unity is not the absence of different opinions, but knowing how to continue to work together despite differences.",s:'The theme is excerpted from "The Dialectical Method of Inner-Party Unity" (November 1957)',e:"The article discusses ways to unite within the party, emphasizing both adhering to principles and accommodating discussions to avoid pushing conflicts to breakdown."},{q:"Who is our enemy? Who are our friends? This question is the primary question of the revolution",s:'"Analysis of the Classes in Chinese Society" (December 1925)',e:"This sentence makes the starting point of revolutionary judgment very clear: first distinguish the main relationship between friends and enemies before deciding on the line, alliance and method of struggle."},{q:"Without correct political views, there is no soul.",s:'"On Correcting Wrong Thoughts within the Party" (December 1929)',e:"No matter how capable the team is, if it does not have a correct political stance and direction, its actions will easily lose its soul and deviate from the goal."},{q:"All true knowledge originates from direct experience",s:'"On Practice" (July 1937)',e:"Real and reliable understanding is not something imagined, but obtained step by step from personal practice and concrete experience."},{q:"Soldiers and people are the foundation of victory",s:'"On Protracted War" (May 1938)',e:"The outcome of a war depends not only on weapons, but also on whether the people are organized and whether the army has the support of the masses."},{q:"Policies and strategies are the life of the party",s:'"On Policy" (December 1940)',e:"The implementation of the route depends on policies and strategies. Once the direction is misaligned, the overall work will lose its vitality."},{q:"The people, and only the people, are the driving force behind creating world history.",s:'"On Coalition Government" (April 1945)',e:"History is not driven by a few heroes alone. The decisive force always comes from the creation and actions of the people."},{q:"Not only are we good at destroying an old world, we will also be good at building a new one",s:"Report of the Second Plenary Session of the Seventh Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (March 1949)",e:"Revolution does not only overthrow the old system, but also has the ability to build a new order, a new country and a new social life."},{q:"Humility makes people progress, pride makes people fall behind",s:'"Speech at the National Congress of the Communist Party of China" (March 1955)',e:"The more humble you can be in the face of your achievements, the easier it will be to continue making progress; once you become complacent, you will often stagnate or even regress."},{q:"Young people are full of vitality and are in their prime, just like the sun at eight or nine o'clock in the morning.",s:'"Conversation when meeting Chinese students in Moscow" (November 1957)',e:"The most valuable thing for young people is their strong vitality and upward ambition. This vitality should be directed towards a cause worth fighting for."},{q:'The most fearful thing in the world is the word "seriousness", and the Communist Party is the most serious about it.',s:`"Speech at the Moscow Conference of Communist and Workers' Parties" (November 1957)`,e:"The most fearful thing about doing things is superficiality and perfunctoryness. Only by being truly sincere and conscientious to the end can things stand and be accomplished."},{q:"Nothing is difficult in the world, as long as you are willing to climb",s:'"Shui Tiao Ge Tou Returns to Jinggangshan" (May 1965)',e:"No matter how difficult things are, as long as you are determined and willing to climb step by step, you will always find a way forward."},{q:"Don\u2019t fight an unprepared battle, don\u2019t fight an uncertain battle",s:`"Strategic Issues in China's Revolutionary War" (December 1936)`,e:"Hitting blindly will only pay a higher price. Truly effective action must be based on adequate preparation and assurance."},{q:"Save yourself and destroy the enemies",s:`"Strategic Issues in China's Revolutionary War" (December 1936)`,e:"War guidance must first preserve the effective forces, and then seize the opportunity to annihilate the enemy. This is the basic principle for handling the relationship between offense and defense."},{q:"The enemy of learning is your own satisfaction",s:'"Transforming Our Learning" (May 1941)',e:'Learning is most easily interrupted by "I already understand." Only by letting go of complacency can your knowledge and judgment continue to grow.'},{q:"The core force leading our cause is the Communist Party of China, and the theoretical basis guiding our thinking is Marxism-Leninism",s:`"Opening Speech of the First Session of the First National People's Congress of the People's Republic of China" (September 1954)`,e:"This sentence summarizes the core of the political direction of New China: what force should be used to lead the cause, and what theory should be used as the ideological basis."},{q:"Whatever the enemy opposes, we must support; whatever the enemy supports, we must oppose",s:'"Interview with Three Correspondents from the Central News Agency, the Sao Tang Pao and the Hsin Min Pao" (September 1939)',e:"This is a simple criterion for judging friend from foe. On matters of fundamental principle, the enemy's attitude itself becomes a reverse coordinate that helps us confirm our own position."},{q:"We must have faith in the masses and we must have faith in the Party. These are two cardinal principles",s:'"On the Question of Agricultural Co-operation" (July 1955)',e:"In major decisions, faith in the masses is the source of strength, and faith in the Party is the organizational guarantee. Neither can be lacking; they are the basic premise for all work."},{q:"A person needs to have a little spirit",s:'"Speech at the National Conference of the Communist Party of China" (March 1955)',e:"Beyond material conditions, what people most cannot do without is a certain spiritual state. In good times or bad, as long as this spirit remains, things can still be carried forward."},{q:"Revolutionary war is a war of the masses; it can be waged only by mobilizing the masses and relying on them",s:'"Be Concerned with the Well-Being of the Masses, Pay Attention to Methods of Work" (January 1934)',e:"The foundation of victory in war lies with the masses. To win battles, the masses must be truly mobilized, organized and relied upon; without the masses, nothing can be done."},{q:"Political work is the lifeblood of all economic work",s:`Editor's note to "A Serious Lesson" ("Socialist Upsurge in China's Countryside", December 1955)`,e:"Without correct political direction, economic work loses its soul. The two are not opposed: political work is precisely what allows economic work to go far and stay on the right path."}];var t=e;export{t as default};
